ce:section.ce:para:
The specimens CSM-1050-C and CSM-850-C underwent characterization through XPS to elucidate their surface chemical composition and specificity. As illustrated in Fig. 3
                        , all four molybdate-loaded samples manifested characteristic peaks corresponding to Mo 3d. The peaks at 228.8 eV and 231.9 eV are ascribed to the 3d5/2 and 3d3/2 orbitals of Mo2+ in Mo2C, respectively [29]. Additionally, Mo2C can be identified by the Mo-C peak at 284 eV in the C1s XPS spectra [30], whereas the peaks at 232.8 eV and 236.1 eV can be attributed to the 3d5/2 and 3d3/2 orbitals of Mo6+ in MoO3, respectively [31,32]. Analysis of peak areas delineates that under the same carbonization temperature, the proportion of Mo2C progressively increases, while that of MoO3 gradually diminishes. Furthermore, the percentage of Mo2C content increases with the dosage of sodium molybdate (Fig. 4
                        ). Moreover, according to the XRD patterns, the in situ growth of molybdenum carbide on the carbonized silk fabric increases with the rise in sodium molybdate dosage (Figure S4). Because Mo2C outperforms MoO3 in hydrogen evolution [33], a sample with higher Mo2C content should be more efficacious in the HER. Subsequent calculations support the fact that CSM-1050–0.5, which has the highest percentage of Mo2C, provides more active sites for HER (Supplementary Materials: Determining the number of active sites per real surface area).
